Think about what you would do if you were Intel and knew that there was a
bug in your P-90 chip.

Lets say that you first learned of the bug 5 months ago during routine
testing.  After a few VERY CLOSED meetings, the insider group decided that
they'd fix the bug in due course, but not delay the shipment of buggy chips
that existed.  Likewise, they would not recall the existing buggy chips.

The reasoning went:  it will be months before we can design around the bug. 
That means more delays with shipping chips.  Likewise, the error is unlikely
to occur.  If the consumers learn of the bug, they won't buy the chips. 
Manufacturers won't buy the chips for their machines, since folks could
return the machines as faulty.  Therefore, it's best for INTEL if we quietly
unload our stock of buggy chips and keep making buggy ones until we have the
bug fixed.

Time would be on Intel's side; time to fix the bug; time until it was
discovered outside the factory; and time to LEARN HOW TO PRODUCE CHIPS
FASTER AND CHEAPER!  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ ^^^^^^^^^^^^ Under a
best case scenario, Intel would fix the bug and also reduce the cost per
chip before the bug became big news.  By limiting who would get replacement
chips to folks already running applications affected by the bug, they would
probably not even have a one-to-one replacement anyway.  Even if they did,
they'd be replacing a chip that they got $500 for wholesale with a chip that
they were presently selling for $300 a chip and still making a larger profit
margin.

As consumers of Intel P-90 chips, our only hope is that Intel comes to the
conclusion that the profits they stand to reap by delaying replacement until
the P-90 becomes obsolete or is produced more cheaply than today, will be
eaten up by litigation and ill-will that will last for generations..

I hope that Intel has folks sufficently wise in the business world to
realize that such a rotten trick on the unsuspecting folks who bought the
P-90 would be a sufficent reason for the scientific and computing community
to make the INTEL INSIDE sticker to be considered a warning label.  

They have the opportunity to do the right thing RIGHT NOW.  What's right?
The answer is to provide a mailing pouch to every owner of a buggy P-90 and
to air ship a bug free P-90 within 24 hours of receipt together with $30 for
a technician's time to replace it.  
 


